# Accessibility Rules

## WCAG 2.2 AA Compliance
- Ensure all content is perceivable, operable, understandable, and robust
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Provide alternative text for images
- Ensure sufficient color contrast
- Make content keyboard accessible

## HTML Structure
- Use proper heading hierarchy (h1, h2, h3, etc.)
- Use semantic elements (nav, main, section, article, aside)
- Include skip links for keyboard navigation
- Use proper form labels and field associations

## Forms
- Associate labels with form controls
- Provide clear error messages
- Use fieldset and legend for grouped fields
- Ensure form validation is accessible

## Navigation
- Provide clear navigation structure
- Use consistent navigation patterns
- Include breadcrumbs where appropriate
- Ensure keyboard navigation works

## Content
- Write clear, concise content
- Use plain language
- Provide instructions and help text
- Use consistent terminology

## Testing
- Test with keyboard navigation
- Test with screen readers
- Use automated accessibility testing tools
- Test with different user agents

## NHS.UK Design System
- Follow NHS.UK design patterns
- Use NHS.UK color palette
- Implement NHS.UK typography
- Follow NHS.UK spacing guidelines
